## 2. Vercel Cron

Cron handlers live at `src/app/api/cron/<job>/route.ts` and are scheduled
in `vercel.json` (or `vercel.ts`).

```typescript
// src/app/api/cron/<job>/route.ts
import { requireCronAuth } from '@/server/api/auth';
import { ok, fail, ErrorCode } from '@/server/api/response';
import * as logger from '@/server/lib/logger';

export const runtime = 'nodejs';
export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic';
export const maxDuration = 300;

export async function GET(req: Request) {
  const auth = requireCronAuth(req);
  if (!auth.ok) return auth.response;

  try {
    const result = await runMyCronJob();
    logger.info('[cron:<job>] completed', result);
    return ok(result);
  } catch (error) {
    logger.error('[cron:<job>] failed', error);
    return fail(ErrorCode.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR);
  }
}
```

**Required:**

- [ ] `requireCronAuth(req)` at the top — verifies `Authorization: Bearer
      <CRON_SECRET>` (Vercel sets this automatically)
- [ ] The job body is idempotent (`withIdempotency` keyed on date if
      partial-failure restart matters)
- [ ] Use `logger.info`/`logger.error` (Vercel ships these to platform logs)
- [ ] Schedule entry exists in `vercel.json` / `vercel.ts`

**Forbidden:**

- ❌ Skipping auth ("it's only invoked by Vercel" is wrong — anyone can hit
     the URL)
- ❌ Long-running work that exceeds `maxDuration` — break into smaller jobs
     or fan out via a queue

