## 3. Webhooks (Stripe, Fal, …)

Webhooks live under `src/app/api/webhooks/<provider>/[<event>/]route.ts`.

### Stripe — raw body required

Stripe signature verification needs the **untouched** request body. Use
`req.text()`, not `req.json()`. Body parsing happens inside the server
handler.

```typescript
// src/app/api/webhooks/stripe/route.ts
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';

import { handleStripeWebhook } from '@/server/handlers/webhooks/stripe-webhook';

export const runtime = 'nodejs';
export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic';
export const maxDuration = 60;

export async function POST(req: Request): Promise<Response> {
  const signature = req.headers.get('stripe-signature');
  const rawBody = await req.text(); // ⚠️ MUST be text, not json

  const result = await handleStripeWebhook({ rawBody, signature });
  return NextResponse.json(result.body, { status: result.status });
}
```

### Fal callbacks

Fal callbacks include a token in the URL or header — verify against
`FAL_WEBHOOK_TOKEN` before doing anything. Like Stripe, dedupe by event id /
request id with `withIdempotency`.

### Required for every webhook

- [ ] Signature / token verified before reading payload
- [ ] Idempotency by external event id via `withIdempotency`
- [ ] Always return HTTP 200 on durably accepted events (so the provider
      doesn't keep retrying); use 4xx only for genuinely malformed input
      that will never succeed
- [ ] Heavy work delegated to `src/server/handlers/webhooks/<provider>-webhook.ts`;
      the route file only owns auth, raw-body extraction, and response
      shaping
- [ ] Never log the raw signing secret or the full payload if it contains
      PII

### Forbidden

- ❌ `req.json()` for Stripe (breaks signature verification)
- ❌ Returning 500 for a payload you've already persisted (the provider
     will replay; you get duplicate side effects)
- ❌ Long-running work in the webhook handler — fan out to a queue and
     return 200 fast

